So I have a question for Tim and this community. It’s about SN8’s Green Flame of Death. We know that the fuel header tank pressure was low, so presumably the fuel flow to the two Raptors that ignited for landing was low. We also know that one of those two flashed green and moments later stopped firing, while the other heroically hung in to the bitter end, even as its copper innards were melting and burning. Ok, got it. Here’s the question.

I keep reading accounts by fairly technically knowledgeable folks that offer this explanation: Low header tank pressure caused low fuel flow, which caused the combustion-chamber mixture to lean out, leading to the presence of excess O2 which oxidized (burned) the Cu liner. And, yeah, yeah, yeah, I get what an oxygen torch is all about, so let’s not go there. Sounds plausible, but... given the complexities of just what exactly goes into creating the fuel/oxygen mix at the injector of a full-flow staged combustion engine, I’m not entirely clear if this would matter much. Us laypeople can’t really know, right?

So, when I heard of Elon’s tweet about the low header-tank fuel pressure, I immediately thought... COOLING. IIRC, the Raptor combustion chamber and nozzle are regeneratively cooled with fuel flow, which has to be kept at a fairly high rate to manage the incredibly high heat flux at the chamber wall and prevent overheating —> melting —> burning —> Green Flame of Death. So, which is it? Lean combustion running too hot, or diminished cooling?

And yeah, gang, please don’t just say “Probably both” - even though it well could be. Is there a reasonably well-informed case to be made for one or the other? I mean, let’s talk turbulent-boundary-layer heat transfer coefficients and the like. Or should I have asked this on Reddit...?

They probably shut down one engine after the other to keep control of the orientation of Starship before doing the belly flop maneuver and dive down in an horizontal orientation. They used thrusters though, but they did not let it tumble around on it's apogee (highest point in flight). They had it under control at the end of the ascent with just one engine, the engine gimbaled and gave the Starship a kick towards the horizontal position and this last engine was shut down. Then the bellyflop manoever with the horizontal dive started.

If they had used 3 engines for 3 to 4 minutes in the ascent and the shut down all 3 at once, it would be not smooth for the vehicle and it would then tumble around for one minute or so until it would come down at a speed where they could use the aerosurfaces. But it would be at any weird rotation speed at any weird position.

But again with throttling down to 2 and then to 1 engine, they had control over the orientation until just before the bellyflop manoever started (before the dive in the horizontal orientation). Then the flaps took over.

With one engine it was already going down a bit, so they had a smooth transition between the ride on the engines and the dive down in the horizontal orientation.

That's at least my observation. It makes sense to me.

But yes, they used the thrusters on the tip of the nose cone a bit after the last engine was shut down to flip the Starship in the horizontal position. But well, maybe there would not have been enough stored compressed gas for the thrusters to use them for one or two minutes. There were just those small "bottles" of compressed gas.
